<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="notes-week-13">
  <title>Week 13</title>

  <subsection>
    <title>Monday</title>
    <p>
      Last week we developed the technology of barycentric subdivision and proved the
      <term>small chains theorem</term>: every homology class is represented by a chain
      whose simplices are entirely contained in members of any chosen open cover. Today
      we cash that in. We prove the <term>excision theorem</term> and the
      <term>Mayer–Vietoris sequence</term>, and then deploy them to compute our first
      family of nontrivial homology groups: <m>H_*(S^n)</m>. Two classical applications
      follow at once — the <term>invariance of dimension</term> and the
      <term>Brouwer fixed point theorem</term>.
    </p>

    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-excision">
      <title>Excision</title>
      <theorem xml:id="thm-excision">
        <title>Excision</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>(X,A)</m> be a pair and let <m>Z\subseteq A</m> be a subspace whose closure
            lies in the interior of <m>A</m>: <m>\overline{Z}\subseteq\mathrm{int}\,A</m>. Then
            the inclusion of pairs <m>(X\setminus Z, A\setminus Z)\hookrightarrow(X,A)</m>
            induces an isomorphism
            <md>
              H_n(X\setminus Z, A\setminus Z)\xrightarrow{\;\sim\;} H_n(X,A)
            </md>
            for every <m>n\ge 0</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
          <p>
            Let <m>B:=X\setminus Z</m>. The hypothesis
            <m>\overline{Z}\subseteq\mathrm{int}\,A</m> implies
            <m>\mathrm{int}\,A\cup\mathrm{int}\,B = X</m>, so
            <m>\mathcal{U}:=\{A,B\}</m> is a cover whose interiors cover <m>X</m>. Let
            <m>C_\bullet^{\mathcal{U}}(X)</m> be the subcomplex of <m>\mathcal{U}</m>-small
            chains and <m>C_\bullet^{\mathcal{U}}(X,A):=C_\bullet^{\mathcal{U}}(X)/C_\bullet(A)</m>
            the corresponding relative complex. By <xref ref="thm-small-chains"/> and the
            five lemma applied to the long exact sequence of the pair, the inclusion
            <m>C_\bullet^{\mathcal{U}}(X,A)\hookrightarrow C_\bullet(X,A)</m> induces an
            isomorphism on homology.
          </p>
          <p>
            On the other hand, every <m>\mathcal{U}</m>-small chain decomposes uniquely (modulo
            chains in <m>A</m>) as a sum of a chain in <m>A</m> and a chain in <m>B</m>. The
            inclusion <m>C_\bullet(B)\hookrightarrow C_\bullet^{\mathcal{U}}(X)</m> therefore
            descends to an isomorphism of relative complexes
            <md>
              C_\bullet(B)/C_\bullet(A\cap B)\;\xrightarrow{\;\sim\;}\;C_\bullet^{\mathcal{U}}(X)/C_\bullet(A).
            </md>
            Since <m>B=X\setminus Z</m> and <m>A\cap B=A\setminus Z</m>, the left side is
            <m>C_\bullet(X\setminus Z, A\setminus Z)</m>. Composing the two isomorphisms yields
            the result.
          </p>
        </proof>
      </theorem>
      <p>
        Excision is the fundamental "locality" property of singular homology: removing a
        well-embedded subspace from both <m>X</m> and <m>A</m> does not change the relative
        homology. It is what distinguishes homology from, say, the homotopy groups
        <m>\pi_n</m>, which are not excisive.
      </p>
    </subsubsection>

    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-mayer-vietoris">
      <title>The Mayer–Vietoris sequence</title>
      <p>
        Let <m>X=A\cup B</m> with <m>A,B</m> subspaces whose interiors cover <m>X</m>. The
        small chains theorem provides a short exact sequence
        <md>
          0\to C_n(A\cap B)\xrightarrow{\;(i,-j)\;} C_n(A)\oplus C_n(B)\xrightarrow{\;k+\ell\;} C_n^{\mathcal{U}}(X)\to 0,
        </md>
        where <m>i\colon A\cap B\hookrightarrow A</m>, <m>j\colon A\cap B\hookrightarrow B</m>,
        <m>k\colon A\hookrightarrow X</m>, and <m>\ell\colon B\hookrightarrow X</m> are the
        inclusions. (Exactness at the middle term is the "decomposition" used in the proof of
        excision; surjectivity at the right is the small chains theorem.) Passing to homology
        via the snake lemma yields:
      </p>
      <theorem xml:id="thm-mayer-vietoris">
        <title>Mayer–Vietoris sequence</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>X=A\cup B</m> with <m>\mathrm{int}\,A\cup\mathrm{int}\,B=X</m>. Then there
            is a long exact sequence
            <md>
              \cdots\to H_n(A\cap B)\xrightarrow{\;(i_*,-j_*)\;} H_n(A)\oplus H_n(B)\xrightarrow{\;k_*+\ell_*\;} H_n(X)
              \xrightarrow{\;\partial_*\;} H_{n-1}(A\cap B)\to\cdots
            </md>
            ending at <m>H_0(X)\to 0</m>. The connecting homomorphism <m>\partial_*</m> is
            described as follows: a class <m>[c]\in H_n(X)</m> can be represented (using the
            small chains theorem) by a cycle <m>c=a+b</m> with <m>a\in C_n(A)</m> and
            <m>b\in C_n(B)</m>; then <m>\partial a=-\partial b</m> is a chain in <m>A\cap B</m>,
            and <m>\partial_*[c]:=[\partial a]\in H_{n-1}(A\cap B)</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
          <p>
            Apply the long exact sequence in homology to the short exact sequence of chain
            complexes displayed above, and use the small chains isomorphism
            <m>H_n^{\mathcal{U}}(X)\cong H_n(X)</m>.
          </p>
        </proof>
      </theorem>
      <p>
        There is also a reduced version: if <m>A\cap B</m> is nonempty, the same argument
        applied to the augmented complexes gives an exact sequence
        <md>
          \cdots\to\widetilde{H}_n(A\cap B)\to\widetilde{H}_n(A)\oplus\widetilde{H}_n(B)\to\widetilde{H}_n(X)\to\widetilde{H}_{n-1}(A\cap B)\to\cdots
        </md>
        We will use the reduced form for spheres.
      </p>
      <p>
        Schematically, the Mayer–Vietoris sequence reads:
        <image width="90%">
          <description>
            The Mayer–Vietoris long exact sequence rendered as a zigzag, with rows for each
            degree connected by the connecting homomorphism.
          </description>
          <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzcd}[column sep=small, row sep=small]
              \cdots \arrow[r] \amp H_n(A\cap B) \arrow[r, "{(i_*,-j_*)}"] \amp H_n(A)\oplus H_n(B) \arrow[r, "k_*+\ell_*"] \amp H_n(X) \arrow[dll, out=-10, in=170, "\partial_*"] \\
              \amp H_{n-1}(A\cap B) \arrow[r] \amp H_{n-1}(A)\oplus H_{n-1}(B) \arrow[r] \amp H_{n-1}(X) \arrow[dll, out=-10, in=170] \\
              \amp \cdots
            \end{tikzcd}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </p>
    </subsubsection>

    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-homology-spheres">
      <title>Homology of spheres</title>
      <theorem xml:id="thm-homology-spheres">
        <title>Homology of <m>S^n</m></title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            For all <m>n\ge 0</m> and <m>k\ge 0</m>,
            <md>
              \widetilde{H}_k(S^n) \cong \begin{cases} \mathbb{Z} \amp \text{if } k=n,\\ 0 \amp \text{otherwise}.\end{cases}
            </md>
            Equivalently, <m>H_0(S^0)\cong\mathbb{Z}^2</m>, <m>H_k(S^0)=0</m> for
            <m>k\ge 1</m>, and for <m>n\ge 1</m>,
            <md>
              H_k(S^n) \cong \begin{cases} \mathbb{Z} \amp \text{if } k=0\text{ or } k=n,\\ 0 \amp \text{otherwise}.\end{cases}
            </md>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
          <p>
            The case <m>n=0</m> is direct: <m>S^0</m> is two points, so
            <m>H_0(S^0)\cong\mathbb{Z}^2</m> and <m>H_k(S^0)=0</m> for <m>k\ge 1</m> by
            <xref ref="prop-h-zero"/> and <xref ref="prop-homology-point"/>. We proceed by
            induction on <m>n\ge 1</m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            Cover <m>S^n</m> by <m>A:=S^n\setminus\{N\}</m> and <m>B:=S^n\setminus\{S\}</m>,
            the complements of the north and south poles. Both <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> are open,
            and stereographic projection gives homeomorphisms <m>A\cong\mathbb{R}^n\cong B</m>.
            In particular <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> are contractible, so
            <m>\widetilde{H}_*(A)=\widetilde{H}_*(B)=0</m> by
            <xref ref="cor-contractible-homology"/>. The intersection <m>A\cap B</m>
            deformation retracts onto the equatorial <m>S^{n-1}</m>; concretely, the radial
            projection <m>(x,t)\mapsto x/|x|</m> realizes <m>A\cap B\simeq S^{n-1}</m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            The reduced Mayer–Vietoris sequence becomes
            <md>
              \cdots\to\widetilde{H}_k(A)\oplus\widetilde{H}_k(B)\to\widetilde{H}_k(S^n)\xrightarrow{\partial_*}\widetilde{H}_{k-1}(S^{n-1})\to\widetilde{H}_{k-1}(A)\oplus\widetilde{H}_{k-1}(B)\to\cdots
            </md>
            which, since the <m>A</m>- and <m>B</m>-terms vanish, collapses to isomorphisms
            <md>
              \partial_*\colon\widetilde{H}_k(S^n)\xrightarrow{\;\sim\;}\widetilde{H}_{k-1}(S^{n-1})\quad\text{for all } k\ge 1.
            </md>
            By induction <m>\widetilde{H}_{k-1}(S^{n-1})</m> is <m>\mathbb{Z}</m> when
            <m>k-1=n-1</m> and zero otherwise, giving the claim. The case <m>k=0</m> is
            handled by path-connectedness of <m>S^n</m> for <m>n\ge 1</m>.
          </p>
        </proof>
      </theorem>
    </subsubsection>

    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-applications-spheres">
      <title>Applications</title>
      <p>
        Two classical consequences are immediate.
      </p>
      <corollary xml:id="cor-invariance-of-dimension">
        <title>Invariance of dimension</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            If <m>m\neq n</m>, then <m>\mathbb{R}^m</m> and <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m> are not
            homeomorphic. More generally, <m>S^m</m> and <m>S^n</m> are not homotopy equivalent
            when <m>m\neq n</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
          <p>
            Suppose <m>m,n\ge 1</m>. If <m>S^m\simeq S^n</m>, then
            <m>\widetilde{H}_*(S^m)\cong\widetilde{H}_*(S^n)</m> by
            <xref ref="cor-homotopy-equivalence-homology"/>; but
            <xref ref="thm-homology-spheres"/> shows these are concentrated in different
            degrees. For <m>\mathbb{R}^m\not\cong\mathbb{R}^n</m>, observe that a
            hypothetical homeomorphism would restrict to a homeomorphism
            <m>\mathbb{R}^m\setminus\{0\}\cong\mathbb{R}^n\setminus\{0'\}</m> for some point
            <m>0'</m>. Since <m>\mathbb{R}^k\setminus\{0\}\simeq S^{k-1}</m>, this would give
            <m>S^{m-1}\simeq S^{n-1}</m>, contradicting the previous statement. The remaining
            cases (<m>m=0</m> or <m>n=0</m>) are handled by counting connected components.
          </p>
        </proof>
      </corollary>
      <corollary xml:id="cor-no-retraction">
        <title>No retraction <m>D^n\to S^{n-1}</m></title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            For <m>n\ge 1</m> there is no continuous retraction <m>r\colon D^n\to S^{n-1}</m>
            (i.e., no continuous <m>r</m> with <m>r|_{S^{n-1}}=\mathrm{id}</m>).
          </p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
          <p>
            Such a retraction would give, with <m>\iota\colon S^{n-1}\hookrightarrow D^n</m>,
            <m>r\circ\iota=\mathrm{id}_{S^{n-1}}</m>, whence
            <m>r_*\circ\iota_*=\mathrm{id}</m> on <m>\widetilde{H}_{n-1}</m>. But
            <m>\widetilde{H}_{n-1}(D^n)=0</m> while
            <m>\widetilde{H}_{n-1}(S^{n-1})\cong\mathbb{Z}</m> — contradiction.
          </p>
        </proof>
      </corollary>
      <theorem xml:id="thm-brouwer-fixed-point">
        <title>Brouwer fixed point theorem</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Every continuous map <m>f\colon D^n\to D^n</m> has a fixed point.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
          <p>
            Suppose <m>f(x)\neq x</m> for all <m>x\in D^n</m>. Define
            <m>r\colon D^n\to S^{n-1}</m> by sending <m>x</m> to the point where the ray from
            <m>f(x)</m> through <m>x</m> meets <m>S^{n-1}</m>. Then <m>r</m> is continuous and
            <m>r|_{S^{n-1}}=\mathrm{id}</m> (a point on the boundary maps to itself), giving a
            retraction <m>D^n\to S^{n-1}</m>. This contradicts
            <xref ref="cor-no-retraction"/>.
          </p>
        </proof>
      </theorem>
      <p>
        On Wednesday we will leverage Mayer–Vietoris (and a related "good pair" version of
        excision) to compute the homology of further spaces — most notably the complex and
        real projective spaces. The key new input there is to understand the effect on
        homology of attaching a single cell, leading to the calculation
        <md>
          H_k(\mathbb{RP}^n) \cong \begin{cases}
            \mathbb{Z} \amp k=0,\\
            \mathbb{Z}/2 \amp 0&lt;k&lt;n,\;k\text{ odd},\\
            0 \amp 0&lt;k&lt;n,\;k\text{ even},\\
            \mathbb{Z} \amp k=n,\;n\text{ odd},\\
            0 \amp k=n,\;n\text{ even},\\
            0 \amp k&gt;n.
          \end{cases}
        </md>
      </p>
    </subsubsection>
  </subsection>

  <subsection>
    <title>Wednesday</title>
    <p>
      Today we put singular homology to work in earnest. We introduce one technical
      ingredient — the <term>good-pair theorem</term>, which identifies the relative
      homology <m>H_*(X,A)</m> with the reduced homology of the quotient
      <m>X/A</m> for nice pairs — and then carry out two cellular computations:
      <m>H_*(\mathbb{CP}^n)</m> (where the answer is uniformly <m>\mathbb{Z}</m> in
      every even degree up to <m>2n</m>) and
      <m>H_*(\mathbb{RP}^n)</m> (where torsion appears for the first time, courtesy of
      a degree-<m>2</m> attaching map).
    </p>

    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-good-pair">
      <title>The good-pair theorem</title>
      <p>
        Let <m>(X,A)</m> be a CW pair, meaning <m>X</m> is a CW complex and
        <m>A\subseteq X</m> is a subcomplex. The homotopy extension property
        of CW pairs (developed in week 10) implies that <m>A</m> has an open neighborhood
        <m>V\subseteq X</m> that deformation retracts onto <m>A</m> — concretely, an
        open thickening one cell at a time. We use this to relate
        <m>H_n(X,A)</m> to the homology of the quotient space.
      </p>
      <theorem xml:id="thm-good-pair">
        <title>Good-pair theorem</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            If <m>(X,A)</m> is a CW pair, then the quotient map <m>q\colon X\to X/A</m>
            induces, for every <m>n\ge 0</m>, an isomorphism
            <md>
              q_*\colon H_n(X, A)\;\xrightarrow{\;\sim\;}\;\widetilde{H}_n(X/A).
            </md>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
          <p>
            Choose an open neighborhood <m>V\supseteq A</m> in <m>X</m> that deformation
            retracts to <m>A</m>. The deformation retraction induces, by
            <xref ref="thm-relative-homotopy-invariance"/> and the five-lemma applied to the
            long exact sequence of the pair, an isomorphism <m>H_n(X,A)\xrightarrow{\sim}H_n(X,V)</m>.
            By excision (<xref ref="thm-excision"/>) applied to <m>Z:=A</m>, whose closure
            is contained in the interior of <m>V</m>,
            <md>
              H_n(X\setminus A,\, V\setminus A)\;\xrightarrow{\;\sim\;}\;H_n(X, V).
            </md>
            The same argument applied inside <m>X/A</m> with <m>A</m> collapsed to the
            basepoint gives <m>H_n(X/A,\, q(V)/A)\cong\widetilde{H}_n(X/A)</m> together
            with an excision isomorphism
            <m>H_n((X/A)\setminus(A/A),\,q(V)/A\setminus(A/A))\xrightarrow{\sim}H_n(X/A,\,q(V)/A)</m>.
            But <m>q</m> restricts to a homeomorphism
            <m>X\setminus A\xrightarrow{\sim}(X/A)\setminus(A/A)</m> sending
            <m>V\setminus A</m> homeomorphically to <m>q(V)/A\setminus(A/A)</m>, so the two
            excised relative groups agree. Composing,
            <md>
              H_n(X,A) \;\cong\; H_n(X\setminus A, V\setminus A) \;\cong\; H_n(X/A, q(V)/A) \;\cong\; \widetilde{H}_n(X/A),
            </md>
            and tracing through the construction shows the composite is <m>q_*</m>.
          </p>
        </proof>
      </theorem>
      <p>
        Combined with the long exact sequence of the pair <m>(X,A)</m>, the good-pair
        theorem says that the homology of a CW complex is built up from the homology of
        its skeleta by a connecting map whose target we can identify with
        <m>\widetilde{H}_*</m> of an explicit quotient. In our applications,
        <m>X/A</m> will be a wedge of spheres — typically just a single sphere — and the
        sequence will be very tractable.
      </p>
    </subsubsection>

    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-homology-cpn">
      <title>Complex projective space</title>
      <p>
        Recall that <m>\mathbb{CP}^n</m> has a CW structure with exactly one cell in each
        even dimension <m>0,2,4,\ldots,2n</m> (and no cells in odd dimensions). The
        <m>2k</m>-skeleton is naturally <m>\mathbb{CP}^k</m>, and the <m>2k</m>-cell is
        attached to <m>\mathbb{CP}^{k-1}</m> via the Hopf map
        <m>S^{2k-1}\to\mathbb{CP}^{k-1}</m>.
      </p>
      <theorem xml:id="thm-homology-cpn">
        <title>Homology of <m>\mathbb{CP}^n</m></title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            For all <m>n\ge 0</m> and <m>k\ge 0</m>,
            <md>
              H_k(\mathbb{CP}^n) \;\cong\; \begin{cases}
                \mathbb{Z} \amp \text{if } 0\le k\le 2n \text{ and } k\text{ is even},\\
                0 \amp \text{otherwise}.
              \end{cases}
            </md>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
          <p>
            By induction on <m>n</m>. The base case <m>n=0</m> is
            <m>\mathbb{CP}^0=\mathrm{pt}</m>, for which the claim is
            <xref ref="prop-homology-point"/>. For the inductive step, consider the CW pair
            <m>(\mathbb{CP}^n,\mathbb{CP}^{n-1})</m>. The quotient
            <m>\mathbb{CP}^n/\mathbb{CP}^{n-1}</m> is obtained by collapsing the boundary
            of the <m>2n</m>-cell to a point and so is homeomorphic to <m>S^{2n}</m>. The
            good-pair theorem (<xref ref="thm-good-pair"/>) and
            <xref ref="thm-homology-spheres"/> yield
            <md>
              H_k(\mathbb{CP}^n,\mathbb{CP}^{n-1})\;\cong\;\widetilde{H}_k(S^{2n})\;=\;
                \begin{cases}\mathbb{Z}\amp k=2n,\\ 0\amp\text{otherwise}.\end{cases}
            </md>
            The long exact sequence of the pair therefore reduces to
            <md>
              \cdots\to H_k(\mathbb{CP}^{n-1})\to H_k(\mathbb{CP}^n)\to H_k(\mathbb{CP}^n,\mathbb{CP}^{n-1})\to H_{k-1}(\mathbb{CP}^{n-1})\to\cdots
            </md>
            with the relative term vanishing except in degree <m>2n</m>. Two cases:
          </p>
          <p>
            <em>Case <m>k\neq 2n,2n-1</m>.</em> Both adjacent relative terms vanish, so
            <m>H_k(\mathbb{CP}^n)\cong H_k(\mathbb{CP}^{n-1})</m>; the inductive hypothesis
            gives the claimed value.
          </p>
          <p>
            <em>Cases <m>k=2n</m> or <m>k=2n-1</m>.</em> The relevant portion of the long
            exact sequence is
            <md>
              0 \to H_{2n}(\mathbb{CP}^{n-1})\to H_{2n}(\mathbb{CP}^n)\to\mathbb{Z}\xrightarrow{\partial}H_{2n-1}(\mathbb{CP}^{n-1})\to H_{2n-1}(\mathbb{CP}^n)\to 0.
            </md>
            By induction, <m>H_{2n}(\mathbb{CP}^{n-1})=0</m> (because <m>2n&gt; 2(n-1)</m>)
            and <m>H_{2n-1}(\mathbb{CP}^{n-1})=0</m> (because <m>2n-1</m> is odd). So the
            sequence collapses to
            <md>
              0\to H_{2n}(\mathbb{CP}^n)\to\mathbb{Z}\to 0\to H_{2n-1}(\mathbb{CP}^n)\to 0,
            </md>
            giving <m>H_{2n}(\mathbb{CP}^n)\cong\mathbb{Z}</m> and
            <m>H_{2n-1}(\mathbb{CP}^n)=0</m>, as claimed.
          </p>
        </proof>
      </theorem>
      <p>
        The computation is unusually painless because the absence of odd-dimensional
        cells makes the connecting map land in a zero group every time. The next example
        is harder because real projective space has cells in every dimension, so the
        connecting map carries genuine information.
      </p>
    </subsubsection>

    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-homology-rpn">
      <title>Real projective space</title>
      <p>
        Recall the CW structure on <m>\mathbb{RP}^n</m> with one <m>k</m>-cell in each
        dimension <m>0\le k\le n</m>. The <m>k</m>-skeleton is <m>\mathbb{RP}^k</m>, and
        the <m>k</m>-cell is attached to <m>\mathbb{RP}^{k-1}</m> via the antipodal
        quotient
        <md>
          \varphi_k\colon S^{k-1}\twoheadrightarrow S^{k-1}/(x\sim -x)\;=\;\mathbb{RP}^{k-1}.
        </md>
        Collapsing <m>\mathbb{RP}^{n-1}</m> in <m>\mathbb{RP}^n</m> identifies the entire
        boundary of the top <m>n</m>-cell to a single point, so
        <m>\mathbb{RP}^n/\mathbb{RP}^{n-1}\cong D^n/\partial D^n\cong S^n</m>. By the
        good-pair theorem,
        <md>
          H_k(\mathbb{RP}^n,\mathbb{RP}^{n-1})\;\cong\;\widetilde{H}_k(S^n)\;=\;\begin{cases}\mathbb{Z}\amp k=n,\\ 0\amp\text{otherwise}.\end{cases}
        </md>
        Plugging into the long exact sequence of the pair, every degree <m>k\notin\{n,n-1\}</m>
        gives an isomorphism <m>H_k(\mathbb{RP}^{n-1})\cong H_k(\mathbb{RP}^n)</m>, while
        the two interesting degrees fit into
        <md>
          0\to H_n(\mathbb{RP}^{n-1})\to H_n(\mathbb{RP}^n)\to\mathbb{Z}\xrightarrow{\partial_n}H_{n-1}(\mathbb{RP}^{n-1})\to H_{n-1}(\mathbb{RP}^n)\to 0.
          \tag{\(*\)}
        </md>
        Everything reduces to identifying the connecting map <m>\partial_n</m>.
      </p>

      <lemma xml:id="lem-rpn-connecting-map">
        <title>The connecting map for <m>(\mathbb{RP}^n,\mathbb{RP}^{n-1})</m></title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            For <m>n\ge 2</m>, the connecting homomorphism
            <m>\partial_n\colon\mathbb{Z}\to H_{n-1}(\mathbb{RP}^{n-1})</m> in the
            sequence (<m>*</m>) sends the generator to the class of the attaching map:
            <md>
              \partial_n(1) \;=\; [\varphi_n]_*\bigl([S^{n-1}]\bigr) \;\in\; H_{n-1}(\mathbb{RP}^{n-1}),
            </md>
            and this class equals
            <md>
              \begin{cases}
                \pm 2\cdot\text{generator} \amp \text{if } n \text{ is even},\\
                0 \amp \text{if } n \text{ is odd}.
              \end{cases}
            </md>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
          <p>
            That <m>\partial_n(1)=[\varphi_n]_*[S^{n-1}]</m> is the standard description of
            the connecting homomorphism for a pair <m>(X,A)</m> obtained by attaching an
            <m>n</m>-cell along <m>\varphi</m>: the boundary of the relative
            <m>n</m>-cycle (a singular simplex parameterizing the cell) is the image of the
            <m>(n-1)</m>-sphere under the attaching map.
          </p>
          <p>
            <em>Case <m>n</m> odd.</em> By induction (the case <m>n-1</m> of this very
            theorem, treating the base case <m>n=1</m> directly: <m>\mathbb{RP}^1=S^1</m>),
            <m>H_{n-1}(\mathbb{RP}^{n-1})=0</m> when <m>n-1</m> is even and <m>n-1\ge 2</m>.
            For <m>n=1</m> the connecting map lands in <m>H_0(\mathbb{RP}^0)\cong\mathbb{Z}</m>
            and is zero because <m>\varphi_1\colon S^0\to\mathrm{pt}</m> is constant. In
            all cases <m>\partial_n=0</m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            <em>Case <m>n</m> even.</em> By induction, <m>H_{n-1}(\mathbb{RP}^{n-1})\cong\mathbb{Z}</m>
            (with <m>n-1</m> odd), and the quotient map
            <m>q\colon\mathbb{RP}^{n-1}\to\mathbb{RP}^{n-1}/\mathbb{RP}^{n-2}\cong S^{n-1}</m>
            induces an isomorphism on <m>H_{n-1}</m> — this is itself a special case of
            the same long exact sequence, applied one dimension down: in the analogue of
            (<m>*</m>) for <m>(\mathbb{RP}^{n-1},\mathbb{RP}^{n-2})</m>, both
            <m>H_{n-1}(\mathbb{RP}^{n-2})</m> and <m>H_{n-2}(\mathbb{RP}^{n-2})\to H_{n-2}(\mathbb{RP}^{n-1})</m>
            are constrained so that
            <m>q_*\colon H_{n-1}(\mathbb{RP}^{n-1})\to\widetilde{H}_{n-1}(S^{n-1})\cong\mathbb{Z}</m>
            is an isomorphism (see the case <m>n-1</m> odd of the inductive hypothesis).
          </p>
          <p>
            Pre-composing with <m>q</m> reduces the calculation to a self-map of
            <m>S^{n-1}</m>:
            <md>
              q\circ\varphi_n \colon S^{n-1}\to\mathbb{RP}^{n-1}\to S^{n-1}.
            </md>
            This composite has degree <m>1+(-1)^n=2</m> (for <m>n</m> even) — geometrically,
            a generic point <m>p\in S^{n-1}</m> has two preimages in <m>S^{n-1}</m> under
            <m>\varphi_n</m> (namely <m>p</m> and its antipode), and the antipodal map on
            <m>S^{n-1}</m> has degree <m>(-1)^n=+1</m>, so both preimages contribute
            with the same sign and the local degrees add. Therefore
            <m>(q\circ\varphi_n)_*=2\cdot\mathrm{id}_\mathbb{Z}</m>, and applying
            <m>q_*^{-1}</m> shows <m>(\varphi_n)_*[S^{n-1}]=\pm 2\cdot\text{generator}</m>
            of <m>H_{n-1}(\mathbb{RP}^{n-1})</m>.
          </p>
        </proof>
      </lemma>

      <theorem xml:id="thm-homology-rpn">
        <title>Homology of <m>\mathbb{RP}^n</m></title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            For all <m>n\ge 1</m> and <m>k\ge 0</m>,
            <md>
              H_k(\mathbb{RP}^n) \;\cong\; \begin{cases}
                \mathbb{Z} \amp k=0,\\
                \mathbb{Z}/2 \amp 0&lt;k&lt;n,\;k\text{ odd},\\
                0 \amp 0&lt;k&lt;n,\;k\text{ even},\\
                \mathbb{Z} \amp k=n,\;n\text{ odd},\\
                0 \amp k=n,\;n\text{ even},\\
                0 \amp k&gt;n.
              \end{cases}
            </md>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
          <p>
            By induction on <m>n</m>. The base case <m>n=1</m> is
            <m>\mathbb{RP}^1\cong S^1</m>, with <m>H_0=\mathbb{Z}</m>,
            <m>H_1=\mathbb{Z}</m>, and higher groups zero — matching the formula
            (<m>n=1</m> is odd, so <m>H_n=\mathbb{Z}</m>).
          </p>
          <p>
            Assume the formula for <m>\mathbb{RP}^{n-1}</m>. For
            <m>k&gt; n</m>, both <m>H_k(\mathbb{RP}^{n-1})</m> and the relative term vanish,
            forcing <m>H_k(\mathbb{RP}^n)=0</m>. For <m>0\le k\le n-2</m>, the relative
            term is also zero on both sides, so
            <m>H_k(\mathbb{RP}^n)\cong H_k(\mathbb{RP}^{n-1})</m>, matching the formula.
            It remains to compute <m>H_n(\mathbb{RP}^n)</m> and <m>H_{n-1}(\mathbb{RP}^n)</m>.
            Recall the exact sequence (<m>*</m>) above:
            <md>
              0\to H_n(\mathbb{RP}^{n-1})\to H_n(\mathbb{RP}^n)\to\mathbb{Z}\xrightarrow{\partial_n}H_{n-1}(\mathbb{RP}^{n-1})\to H_{n-1}(\mathbb{RP}^n)\to 0.
            </md>
            By induction <m>H_n(\mathbb{RP}^{n-1})=0</m> (since <m>n&gt; n-1</m>), so
            the sequence simplifies to
            <md>
              0\to H_n(\mathbb{RP}^n)\to\mathbb{Z}\xrightarrow{\partial_n}H_{n-1}(\mathbb{RP}^{n-1})\to H_{n-1}(\mathbb{RP}^n)\to 0.
            </md>
            We split on the parity of <m>n</m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            <em>Case <m>n</m> odd, <m>n\ge 3</m>.</em> By induction
            <m>H_{n-1}(\mathbb{RP}^{n-1})=0</m> (since <m>n-1</m> is even and
            <m>n-1=n-1</m> is the top dimension of <m>\mathbb{RP}^{n-1}</m>, and the formula
            says this group vanishes). The exact sequence collapses to
            <m>0\to H_n(\mathbb{RP}^n)\to\mathbb{Z}\to 0\to H_{n-1}(\mathbb{RP}^n)\to 0</m>,
            yielding <m>H_n(\mathbb{RP}^n)=\mathbb{Z}</m> and
            <m>H_{n-1}(\mathbb{RP}^n)=0</m>. Both agree with the formula.
          </p>
          <p>
            <em>Case <m>n</m> even, <m>n\ge 2</m>.</em> By induction
            <m>H_{n-1}(\mathbb{RP}^{n-1})\cong\mathbb{Z}</m> (since <m>n-1</m> is odd and
            <m>n-1</m> is the top dimension). By
            <xref ref="lem-rpn-connecting-map"/>, the connecting map
            <m>\partial_n\colon\mathbb{Z}\to\mathbb{Z}</m> is multiplication by
            <m>\pm 2</m> — in particular, injective with image <m>2\mathbb{Z}</m>.
            Therefore <m>H_n(\mathbb{RP}^n)=\ker\partial_n=0</m> and
            <m>H_{n-1}(\mathbb{RP}^n)=\mathbb{Z}/2\mathbb{Z}</m>. Both match the formula.
          </p>
        </proof>
      </theorem>

      <p>
        The pattern of homology groups
        <md>
          \mathbb{Z},\;\mathbb{Z}/2,\;0,\;\mathbb{Z}/2,\;0,\;\mathbb{Z}/2,\;\ldots
        </md>
        for <m>\mathbb{RP}^\infty</m> is striking: torsion appears in every odd
        positive degree and nothing else survives. It is a first-time
        encounter with non-free homology, and a first sign that
        <m>\mathbb{Z}</m>-coefficients are not always the cleanest place to work.
        Coefficients in <m>\mathbb{Z}/2</m>, where antipodal-degree subtleties disappear, give
        <md>
          H_k(\mathbb{RP}^n;\mathbb{Z}/2) \;\cong\; \mathbb{Z}/2 \quad\text{for all } 0\le k\le n,
        </md>
        a phenomenon that motivates the systematic study of <term>cohomology with arbitrary
        coefficients</term> in a follow-up course.
      </p>
    </subsubsection>

    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-coda">
      <title>Coda</title>
      <p>
        We have come a long way: starting from open sets in January, working through the
        categorical apparatus of point-set topology, the homotopical language of CW
        complexes, the algebraic machinery of chain complexes, and finally arriving at
        excision and Mayer–Vietoris.
      </p>
      <p>
        From here the natural continuations diverge. <term>Cellular homology</term>
        re-organizes today's computation into a finite chain complex one can write down
        directly from the CW structure. <term>Cohomology</term> introduces a
        contravariant theory with a multiplicative structure (the cup product) that
        distinguishes spaces whose ordinary homology agrees. Universal coefficients,
        Künneth, and the Eilenberg–Steenrod axioms unify the picture. And the homotopy
        groups <m>\pi_n(X)</m>, which we have steered around all year because they fail
        excision, return as the deepest invariants of all. A second-semester sequel
        would visit each of these in turn.
      </p>
      <p>
        For now: thank you, and well done.
      </p>
    </subsubsection>
  </subsection>

</section>
